An example of the so—called ³ compa- ratio compendiaria,' by which the property belonging to the person or thing is directly compared with the person or with the thing itself. This brachylogy is often employed to avoid the awkward repetition of the same word or the unidiomatic substitution of a demonstrative pronoun. In Tacitus the construction is rare, e. g.
